abstract.value: The Arvid Paulson Papers represent Paulson's attempts to bring the work of August Strindberg and Henrik Ibsen to a twentieth century American public. The collection contains his correspondence with actors, publishers and producers, the manuscripts of his translations, some of his published criticism on Strindberg and Ibsen as well as that of other authors. Finally, it contains miscellaneous theatre memorabilia culled from a long life spent going to the theatre, perfoming in plays and occasionally even producing them himself.

p.value: Materials are open to researchers. Please contact the Fales Library and Special Collections, fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.

Published citations should take the following form:<lb/><lb/>
Identification of item,  date (if known); The Arvid Paulson Papers; MSS 043; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

Arvid Paulson (1888-1977) was an author, translator and actor. Born in Helsingborg, Sweden, he emigrated to the United States in 1904. Though he performed in many plays written by Strindberg and Ibsen, he is perhaps best known as a translator of their work.

<emph render="bold">Series I: Correspondence</emph> contains Paulson's correspondence with various producers, actors and publishers, 1917-1977. <lb/>
<emph render="bold">Series II: Manuscripts</emph> contains the manuscripts for Paulson's translations of Ibsen, Strindberg and other Scandinavian writers; it also contains Paulson's collection of Ibsen ephemera.<lb/><emph render="bold">Series III: Publications</emph> contains Paulson's and other writers' published articles about Strindberg.<lb/><emph render="bold">Series IV: Printed Matter and Memorabilia</emph> contains programs, playbills, photographs and miscellaneous other material relating to productions of Strindberg's and Ibsen's plays in Sweden and America, as well as more generally to the twentieth century American theatre.<lb/><emph render="bold">Series V: Paulson</emph> contains some of Paulson's personal papers.

Series II contains the mss. of Paulson's translations of Henrik Ibsen, August Strindberg and other Scandinavian authors. Subseries A contains Paulson's translations of Ibsen, as well as miscellaneous Ibsen ephemera collected by Paulson; the ephemera includes playbills, postcards and criticism. Series II, Subseries B contains Paulson's mss. translations of Strindberg; subseries C contains the same material, this time in drafts prepared for publication. Subseries D contains Paulson's translations of Vilhelm Moberg, Knut Hamsun, Gustav Geijerstam and other Scandinavian authors. Subseries E contains miscellaneous manuscripts.

Series III contains criticism and translations published by Paulson and other writers in Swedish and American periodicals. Subseries A contains Paulson's articles on Strindberg, as well as Paulson's translations of Strindberg, Selma Lagerlof and Arvid Skappel. Subseries B contains articles on Strindberg and on Strindberg studies by other authors, as well as a 1913 translation of Strindberg's "Half a Sheet of Paper.

Series IV contains playbills, photographs, tickets, press clippings and other material from Paulson's life as a producer, performer and theater-goer; in addition it contains publicity material for his books and misc. Strindberg memorabilia. Subseries A contains playbills, photographs and tickets from performances of Strindberg's plays in Sweden and America, 1918-1979; Paulson either acted in or supplied the translations for some of these productions. Subseries A also contains misc. material from Paulson's life in the theatre, such as a 1941 manual for theatre staff and an assortment of actors' periodicals. Subseries B contains Strindberg memorabilia.
